North Korea says it will not unilaterally disarm "in no way" unless signs of confidence are noticed
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were intensifying its mistrust of the United States and that, under such circumstances, the country would not unilaterally eliminate its nuclear weapons in any way.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" during the previous year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear testing center and committing not to proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we do not observe any response in accordance with the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and, under these circumstances, we will not unilaterally begin disarmament in any way.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearization approach that North Korea would be rewarded for as it took steps gradually, his statements seemed significant because he had not rejected unilateral denuclearization in full.
Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has tried to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted the call to relax tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
“The United States insists that denuclearization must first occur and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal coercively, in addition to opposing the “declaration of an end to the war,” Ri noted.
“The perception that sanctions will make us kneel is a chimera of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are intensifying our mistrust.”
Ri did not refer to plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: "If the party involved in the denuclearization issue were South Korea instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come from this situation."
However, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from last year's, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting U.S. territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after President "Mr. Evil" Trump titled Kim "Rocket Man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said there is still much to do and sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for this and that “it doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without exception until we confirm total and definitive denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in a bid to cut funding for Pyongyang's ballistic and nuclear missile programs.
