Harvard Students Take a Course on Resting Habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the ever-expanding culture of studying all night long, stimulated by caffeine.
One academic noted that often the world’s number one university students are clueless about the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after having a talk about the impact that sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the talk, a girl approached me and said, ‘Why are they telling me all this now, in my last year?’
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, implemented for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, in addition to overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, bamboo and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how it affects sports performance in lack of sleep, and about the importance of maintaining a sleeping routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Next, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in staying awake all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure that students are suffering from makes sleep deprivation an ever-increasing problem.
Making sure to enjoy good quality sleep for long enough should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in inanimate mode and always makes students gain.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course across the campus.
The next step, he expects, is to ask postgraduate students to undertake a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of circadian rhythm.
