Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page of the "Sunday Morning" Almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and counting... the day the physicist of the future, Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually gave rise to the device we know as the "Geiger counter".
The Geiger counter, which has been a pillar of science ever since, also became a staple of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, seemingly failed cowboy physicists:
Man: "What inside is this?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, which is used to find radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you can hear the effects of the atoms that emanate from radioactivity to minerals."
Evans: "I'm sure it's exploding now!"
Hans Geiger died in 1945, a few days after his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name is still alive.
A New Cancer Vaccine May Teach Your Immune System to ‘See’ Malignant Cells
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to “see” and remove malignant cells
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells as part of the treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory.
You can "see" a common protein in many cancers and then re-inject them
A trial vaccine is showing promising results in patients with various types of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells, saw the ovarian cancer that she suffered from for more than 18 months disappear.
The method involves extracting a patient's immune cells, altering them in the laboratory to be able to "see" a protein present in many types of cancer (HER2), and subsequently re-injecting them.
According to Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, USA: “The results we have obtained suggest that we have a promising vaccine.”
The HER2 protein "favours the growth of several types of cancer," including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancers, Professor Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach consisting of extracting immune cells from patients and "teaching" these cells how to treat cancer cells has worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
