The National Foundation spies on the secret life of bats
A new research carried out on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to discover how bats use the landscape to feed themselves.
The findings are expected to provide new data on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help in future conservation activities.
The study of scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland will follow soprano and common bats, as well as northern eardrums and water bats in the Botanical Garden of Inverewe, located in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations of the property to monitor the activities of bats during the season.
Volunteers and staff from the UK National Health Service will also conduct mobile surveys with portable detectors.
The analysis of the sound of the recordings by experts will determine the sound frequency of the bats and what each species does.
With this information, a report and a map of the habitat will be created to create a detailed image on a scale of the landscape of your behavior.
Rob Dewar, natural conservation adviser at the National Foundation of Scotland, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating meadows, and how to improve the maintenance of forests for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the rest of the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
The construction and restoration of buildings threaten the bats, as they affect the nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do paper-killing masks and chemical treatments used in building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
In fact, cats are not blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they have to catch a prey.
They use a sophisticated echo location technique to locate insects and obstacles that interfere with their flight.
The National Foundation of Scotland, responsible for taking care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts with appropriate training, who conduct surveys, nest inspections and, sometimes, rescues on a regular basis.
The organisation has even created Scotland's first and only bat reserve on the Threave Estate, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The farm's administrator, David Thompson, claims that it is the ideal territory for the species.
“Here at Threave, we have a large area for bats,” he says.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and a good habitat.
But we still don’t know many aspects of bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.”
It notes the importance of checking for bats before doing property maintenance tasks, as it may be that the possible unintentional destruction of a single maternity nest kills more than 400 females and young people, which could lead to the disappearance of an entire local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, attack them, disturb them and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an official of the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, has encouraged people to take a step forward to help.
He said: “We still have a lot to learn from bats and, in the case of some of our species, we don’t have enough data on their population.”
