Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people have died due to a strong earthquake and tsunami that shook the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, according to authorities. The number of deaths is expected to increase.
As communications are cut off, aid units have been unable to obtain information from the Donggala regency, an area north of Palu closest to the epicentre of the 7.5 magnitude earthquake.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people have been evacuated following the disaster.
Below are some important data about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Celebes:
Palu is the capital of the Central Celebes province, located at the end of a narrow bay on the western coast of the island of Celebes, with an estimated population of 379,800 people in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a regency that stretches along more than 300 km of coastline to the northwest of the island of Celebes.
The Regency, an administrative region less than a province, had an approximate population of 299,200 people in 2017.
Fishing and agriculture are the pillars of the economy of Central Celebes Province, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the coast of the other end of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have suffered several tsunamis in the last 100 years, according to Indonesia's disaster mitigation agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami occurred in western Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific belt of fire and earthquakes usually occur there with a certain frequency.
The following are the major earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On 26 December, a major earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Ace province, north of Sumatra, caused a tsunami that affected 14 countries and killed 226,000 people on the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Thousands of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, causing a tsunami that destroyed the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake shook a pop area of the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A magnitude 7.5 earthquake rocked one of the islands of Mentawai off the coast of Sumatra, causing a tsunami of up to 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A mild earthquake affected the Regency of Pidie Jaya in Aceh and caused destruction and panic as the population recalled the devastation of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, no tsunami occurred, but more than 100 people died due to the buildings that fell.
2018: A series of major earthquakes occurred on the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok that killed more than 500 people, mostly in the north of the island.
The quake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists trapped temporarily.
